'''Nakagawa Shrine''' (なかがわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Nakatsugawa|Q844052|qid=Q844052|1=Nakatsugawa}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|qid=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}. Its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Kami|Q11619891|qid=Q11619891|lt=Kukuri-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Kikurihime}}
*{{ill|lt=Izanami|Q682306|qid=Q682306|lt=Izanami-no-Mikoto|1=Izanami}}
*{{ill|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime|Q1781862|qid=Q1781862|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Konohanasakuya-hime}}

=== Annual festival ===
2nd Sunday of April. Nakatsugawa Taiko, Kamiyo-shishi, and others are dedicated.

=== History ===
This is Nakagawa Shrine, a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki-listed shrine|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} of {{ill|lt=Ena District|Q3030924|qid=Q3030924|1=Ena District, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|qid=Q864156|1=Mino Province}}. It is the {{ill|lt=ubusunagami|Q1392097|qid=Q1392097|1=Ubusunagami}} of Nakatsugawa City.

Founding date is unknown. Since {{ill|lt=Mount Ena|Q1339920|qid=Q1339920|1=Mount Ena}} is regarded as the place where {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu|1=UNKNOWN}}'s placenta was placed ({{ill|lt=Ena Shrine|Q11492453|qid=Q11492453|1=Ena Shrine (Nakatsugawa)}}), this area is thought to have long been sacred, and there is also a tradition that {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|qid=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}} was born here.

Formerly it was called Hakusan-sha or Susukinomori. One theory says it began with worship of a goddess of the {{ill|lt=Kiso River|Q779607|qid=Q779607|1=Kiso River}}, and that this deity was later changed into three goddess deities (Kukuri-hime, Izanami, Konohanasakuya-hime).

The current reading is "Nakagawa," but in older times it was also read "Nakawa" and "Nakatsukawa," and one theory says this gave rise to the place name Nakatsugawa.

Also, the {{ill|lt=Nakatsugawa River (Gifu)|Q11366440|qid=Q11366440|lt=Nakatsugawa|1=Nakatsu River}}, a tributary of the Kiso River, was formerly called Nakagawa.

According to "Mino Kodō Misakagoe-ki" and "Nakagawa Kyūki," it was originally the main Kumano Gongen shrine, and at rebuilding Hakusan Daigongen (Kukuri-hime) was made principal while Kumano (Izanami) and Fuji (Konohanasakuya-hime) were enshrined in the aiden; a {{ill|lt=bettōji|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}} called '''Taishō-ji''' managed the shrine.

The temple site is on the southern foot of Nakagawa Shrine. It is now a residential area, but one hōkyōintō and one gorintō remain. White porcelain-like sherds (yamachawan) were collected from a garden on the ridge connected to Nakagawa Shrine, but it is unclear whether they indicate kiln remains or a dwelling site.

According to "Mino Kodō Misakagoe-ki," in {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1574|Q6680|qid=Q6680|1=1574}}), Hakusan Daigongen was burned by war during {{ill|lt=Takeda Katsuyori|Q662482|qid=Q662482|1=Takeda Katsuyori}}'s invasion of {{ill|lt=Tōnō|Q7862707|qid=Q7862707|1=Tōnō}}. At that time the middle seat was Hakusan, left Kumano, right Fuji; the ornate shrine and monks' quarters were burned, and only graves of the priest and shrine monks remained.

It was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Enpō|Q1145735|qid=Q1145735|1=Enpō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1677|Q7631|qid=Q7631|1=1677}}).

Possibly because of this, in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}} only three shrines are seen for {{ill|lt=Nakatsugawa-juku|Q2420820|qid=Q2420820|1=Nakatsugawa-juku}} on the {{ill|lt=Nakasendō|Q1154479|qid=Q1154479|1=Nakasendō}} (Hachiman shrine, Hakusan Gongen shrine, Shinmei shrine), and the name Nakagawa Shrine disappears. It is thought to have been divided and re-enshrined sometime between the Sengoku-period destruction and the early Edo period.

In the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji period|1=Meiji era|qid=Q3125096}}, the "{{ill|lt=Hakusan Gongen|Q11579578|qid=Q11579578|lt=Hakusan Gongen shrine|1=Hakusan Gongen}}" came to be treated as Nakagawa Shrine, and in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}}) it became a village shrine.

The current honden is the rebuild of Enpō 5 (1677), but the haiden and related buildings were not rebuilt then. In {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 14 ({{ill|lt=2002|Q1987|qid=Q1987|1=2002}}), the haiden and naoraiden were rebuilt and the precinct was also improved.

=== Access ===
*About 800 m from {{ill|lt=Nakatsugawa Station|Q5359511|qid=Q5359511|1=Nakatsugawa Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Chūō Main Line|Q1078110|qid=Q1078110|1=Chūō Main Line}}

=== Other ===
*Directly beneath Nakagawa Shrine precinct runs an uphill-line {{ill|lt=tunnel|Q44377|qid=Q44377|1=Tunnel}} of the Chūō Main Line.

